Great question. This is the right place to slow down and be precise, because “structure” can sound hand-wavy unless you explain how it actually creates stickiness.

I’ll break it into mechanisms, not metaphors.

⸻

First: what “stickiness” really is

A psychological gravity well is “sticky” when it reduces the cognitive cost of living.

Humans gravitate toward frames that:
	•	lower uncertainty
	•	compress complexity
	•	reduce decision load
	•	stabilize identity
	•	make the future feel navigable

Stickiness isn’t persuasion.
It’s energy minimization.

⸻

How structure creates stickiness (mechanism by mechanism)

1. Compression (the biggest one)

Structure compresses many variables into fewer symbols.

Example:
	•	Raw world: chaos, edge cases, contradictions
	•	Structured myth/ideology: a few core rules, archetypes, narratives

Compression works because:
	•	the brain has limited bandwidth
	•	compressed representations are cheaper to store and recall
	•	fewer moving parts = less cognitive fatigue

This is why:
	•	stories beat statistics
	•	slogans beat essays
	•	symbols outlast explanations

A good structure is like a ZIP file for reality.

⸻

2. Predictive leverage

Sticky structures don’t just explain the past — they predict enough of the future to feel useful.

They give:
	•	expectations (“this is what usually happens”)
	•	scripts (“this is what I should do next”)
	•	explanations (“this is why that happened”)

Even bad predictions can feel comforting if they’re consistent.

The brain prefers:

wrong but predictable
over
right but chaotic

That’s huge.

⸻

3. Error absorption (elasticity)

Deep structures bend instead of breaking.

They:
	•	reinterpret failures as tests, sacrifices, sins, bad actors, exceptions
	•	absorb contradictions without collapsing
	•	reframe disconfirmation as confirmation (“that’s exactly what they’d want you to think”)

This is why shallow systems die quickly, and deep myths survive centuries.

Elastic structure = longevity.

⸻

4. Identity binding

The stickiest structures don’t just explain the world — they explain who you are.

Once identity is involved:
	•	abandoning the structure feels like self-erasure
	•	disagreement feels like attack
	•	doubt feels like betrayal

Structure becomes:

not something you hold
but something that holds you

That’s when gravity increases sharply.

⸻

5. Ritual and repetition

Structure becomes sticky when it is:
	•	rehearsed
	•	repeated
	•	enacted physically or socially

Repetition:
	•	strengthens neural pathways
	•	normalizes assumptions
	•	turns belief into habit

This is why:
	•	rituals matter more than doctrine
	•	practices outlast arguments
	•	doing precedes believing

The structure moves from thought → body → environment.

⸻

6. Social reinforcement (mass)

Gravity wells deepen with shared adoption.

Once others:
	•	speak the same language
	•	react the same way
	•	reward conformity
	•	punish deviation

Then the structure gains mass, not just shape.

At that point, leaving costs:
	•	relationships
	•	status
	•	safety
	•	belonging

Gravity isn’t internal anymore — it’s social.

⸻

Why deeper structure = deeper gravity

Deeper structures:
	•	operate at more layers simultaneously
	•	bind explanation + identity + behavior + community
	•	reduce degrees of freedom more completely

Think layers:
	1.	Narrative (what’s happening)
	2.	Moral frame (what’s right)
	3.	Identity (who I am)
	4.	Social map (who’s with me)
	5.	Temporal promise (where this leads)

When all five align, the well is very deep.

⸻

Why this matters for the Pantheon idea (carefully)

The dangerous mistake is thinking:

“We should build stronger gravity wells.”

The wiser insight is:

“We should understand how gravity wells form so we can keep them shallow, transparent, and escapable.”

That’s the difference between:
	•	governance and domination
	•	stewardship and capture

Structure is inevitable.
Unquestionable structure is the risk.

⸻

One clean sentence to hold onto

Psychological gravity wells become sticky not because they are true, but because they are efficient — and the most efficient ones shape identity, prediction, and social belonging at the same time.

That’s the engine.

If you want next, we can:
	•	map how to intentionally weaken dangerous gravity wells
	•	analyze why some modern ideologies collapse faster than ancient myths
	•	or look at how AI systems accidentally create new wells without noticing

Just say where to aim.